and","Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1255–1287":"1255–1287","1255–Female":"1255–Overleden","1282–Female":"1282–Overleden","1284–1345":"1284–1345","1286–Male":"1286–Overleden","1288–Female":"1288–Overleden","1225–1287":"1225–1287","1230–Female":"1230–Overleden","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1250":"1250","abt. 1282":"circa 1282","1282":"1282","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","ABT 1286":"circa 1286","1345":"1345","1255":"1255","Abt 1287":"circa 1287","1288":"1288","1287":"1287","Bromwick Castle, Aston Manor, Warwickshire, England":"Aston Manor, Warwickshire, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwick, Eng.":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1255–1287":"1255–1287","1255–Female":"1255–Deceased","1282–Female":"1282–Deceased","1284–1345":"1284–1345","1286–Male":"1286–Deceased","1288–Female":"1288–Deceased","1225–1287":"1225–1287","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1250":"1250","abt. 1282":"about 1282","1282":"1282","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","ABT 1286":"about 1286","1345":"1345","1255":"1255","Abt 1287":"about 1287","1288":"1288","1287":"1287","Bromwick Castle, Aston Manor, Warwickshire, England":"Aston Manor, Warwickshire, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwick, Eng.":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bromwich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from West Bromwich (Staffs) or Castle and Little Bromwich (Warwicks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Brommage","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]},{"name":"Brumage","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bromage  ."]},{"name":"Bromage","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): habitational name from West Bromwich in Staffordshire, or Castle and Little Bromwich in Warwickshire, named in Old English with <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ (the shrub) + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying dairy farm’. Compare   Brumage  ."]},{"name":"Brimage","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Brumage  . This name is comparatively rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bromige","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Bromwich was born in 1255, in Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England, his father, Henry de Bromwich, was 30 and his mother, Madam Bromwyz, was 25. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Isabella of Bromwich. He died in 1287, in Aston Manor, Warwickshire, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1255–1287":"1255–1287","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1284–1345":"1284–1345","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1288–Female":"1288–Surnud","1225–1287":"1225–1287","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1250":"1250","abt. 1282":"umbes 1282","1282":"1282","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","ABT 1286":"umbes 1286","1345":"1345","1255":"1255","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","1288":"1288","1287":"1287","Bromwick Castle, Aston Manor, Warwickshire, England":"Aston Manor, Warwickshire, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwick, Eng.":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1255–1287":"1255–1287","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1284–1345":"1284–1345","1286–Male":"1286–Kuollut","1288–Female":"128